                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d87">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.92/259: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Thailand</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-21T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 21, 1941—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>31. According to a telegram of February 15 from Vichy,<note n="19"
                        xml:id="d87fn1">Telegram No. 198, February 15, 5 p.m., not printed.</note>
                    based upon information supplied by the French Government, the French Ambassador
                    at Tokyo recently refused to continue the negotiations for a Thai-Indochinese
                    settlement unless the Thai attitude be moderated; a notable improvement in the
                    Japanese attitude resulted; the Japanese Chargé d’Affaires at Vichy has informed
                    the French Government that the Japanese Minister at Bangkok has been instructed
                    to insist on moderation of the Thai attitude and on withdrawal of Thai troops
                    who recently crossed the Mekong in Luang Prabang.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
